            Phoridae
is a considerably diverse family of tiny flies (
0.4–6 mm
) with about 4500 species worldwide (

). The phorids have a wide array of ecological habits especially in the larval stage when they can be saprophagous, predators, parasitoids, kleptoparasites, herbivores or parasites (

). Phorids are highly abundant in natural habitats and they may be among the most speciose families of flies in certain areas (

; 

). As usual for megadiverse families of small insects, the 
Phoridae
are largely unknown. The actual number of species is estimated as high as ten times the number of described species (

), highly abundant species are still unknown (

) and new genera are frequently recognized and described (e.g., 

; 

).

All specimens studied were collected with Malaise traps, preserved in alcohol, and subsequently dried and mounted with HMDS (
). The specimens collected by the SISBIOTA project in the west of Brazil belong to the Museu de Zoologia da USP, Brazil ( MZUSP ). The other specimens studied are from the Coleç„o de Entomologia, Centro de Coleções Taxonômicas da Universidade Federal de Minas Gerais , Belo Horizonte, Brazil ( UFMG ). General body morphological structures are referred to by the terms of
while phallus structures by the terms of
with the amendments specified in
. Hypopygia were removed, cleared in lactic acid (
) and illustrated under compound microscope using glycerin temporary preparations in triangular cavity slides (
). Some structures were chosen for SEMs preparation for better visualization including the phallus, which was removed from the hypopygium in glycerin and dehydrated in alcohol 70%, 70%, and absolute (15 minutes in each) before preparing it in the SEM stub.

Besides usual morphological examination, wing interference patterns (WIPs) were checked for interspecific variation following some studies that are finding useful taxonomic information on these patterns (Shevtsova & Hansson 2011; Shevtsova 
et al
. 2011; 

). The WIPs were observed and photographed according to the methodology of 

. In order to obtain a clearer and more direct WIPs comparison, the WIPs observed in a horizontal intermediate line between wing veins M 
1
and M 
2
were illustrated and compared (as in 

